		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Logical volume management</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_storage" title="Computer storage" class="mw-redirect">computer storage</a>, <b>logical volume management</b> or <b>LVM</b> is a method of allocating space on <a href="/wiki/Mass_storage" title="Mass storage">mass storage</a> devices that is more flexible than conventional <a href="/wiki/Partition_(computing)" title="Partition (computing)" class="mw-redirect">partitioning</a> schemes. In particular, a volume manager can concatenate, <a href="/wiki/Data_striping" title="Data striping">stripe</a> together or otherwise combine partitions into larger virtual ones that can be resized or moved, possibly while it is being used.</p>
<p>Volume management is one of many forms of <a href="/wiki/Storage_Virtualization" title="Storage Virtualization" class="mw-redirect">storage virtualization</a>, the one implemented as a layer in the OS <a href="/wiki/Device_driver" title="Device driver">disk driver stack</a>.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
<div id="toctitle">
